matrix (elements should always keep the same)

mat <- matrix(1:20, ncol = 4)
mat
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    1    6   11   16
## [2,]    2    7   12   17
## [3,]    3    8   13   18
## [4,]    4    9   14   19
## [5,]    5   10   15   20
# pick up a single element
mat[5,2]
## [1] 10
# pick up a col
mat[,3]
## [1] 11 12 13 14 15
#pick up a row
mat[2,]
## [1]  2  7 12 17
#pick up several rows
mat[2:4,]
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    2    7   12   17
## [2,]    3    8   13   18
## [3,]    4    9   14   19
# reassign the value
mat[4,] <- rep(100,4)
mat
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    1    6   11   16
## [2,]    2    7   12   17
## [3,]    3    8   13   18
## [4,]  100  100  100  100
## [5,]    5   10   15   20
# name the col name
colnames(mat) <- c('one','two','three','four')
mat
##      one two three four
## [1,]   1   6    11   16
## [2,]   2   7    12   17
## [3,]   3   8    13   18
## [4,] 100 100   100  100
## [5,]   5  10    15   20
mat[,'four']
## [1]  16  17  18 100  20
# name the row name
rownames(mat) <- c('a','b','c','d','e')
mat
##   one two three four
## a   1   6    11   16
## b   2   7    12   17
## c   3   8    13   18
## d 100 100   100  100
## e   5  10    15   20
# tick out some elements
mat[,c(-1,-2)]
##   three four
## a    11   16
## b    12   17
## c    13   18
## d   100  100
## e    15   20

z

## [3,]     3      6     9

rbind(z[1,], 1:3)

handing the missing value

NA is different from NULL

length(c(-1,0,NA,5))
## [1] 4
length(c(-1,0,NULL,5))
## [1] 3

remove the NA

t <- c(-1,0,NA,5) 
mean(t)
## [1] NA
mean(t,na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 1.333333
## null is just do not exist
s <- c(-1,0,NULL,5) 
mean(s)
## [1] 1.333333
## to judge whether it is na
is.na(t)
## [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE
## inf and not a nuber(nan)
c(3/0,0/0)
## [1] Inf NaN
x = NULL
x[1] = 'blue'
x[2] = 'red'
x[4] = 'green'
x
## [1] "blue"  "red"   NA      "green"
